Below is a **single, self‑contained unit** that you can drop into your project.  
It contains

* a **public C header** (`blocksci_c.h`) that a C programmer will include, and  
* a **C++ implementation** (`blocksci_c.cpp`) that ships the thin wrapper around the real BlockSci C++ iterator.

The wrapper is deliberately **minimal, zero‑allocation per‑block and fully in‑line**, so the hot path stays as fast as the native C++ iterator.  
All the “public” objects that C sees are opaque pointers (`bsci_iter_t` and `bsci_block_t`).  
The only thing a C caller can do is ask the iterator to walk the whole chain and run a callback for each block; the callback receives a read‑only view of the block and a user‑supplied context pointer.

---  

## 1️⃣ Public C header – `blocksci_c.h`

```c
/*=====================================================================
 *  blocksci_c.h
 *  C bindings for BlockSci – per‑block iteration
 *
 *  SPDX‑License-Identifier: MIT
 *====================================================================*/

#ifndef BLOCKSCI_C_H
#define BLOCKSCI_C_H

#ifdef __cplusplus
extern "C" {
#endif

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
 * Opaque handles – the real objects live in C++ land.
 * -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
typedef struct bsci_iter_t  bsci_iter_t;   /* iterator over the whole chain */
typedef struct bsci_block_t bsci_block_t; /* read‑only view of a single block */

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
 * Callback signature.
 *
 *   block   – pointer to a read‑only block view; never NULL.
 *   user_data – the opaque pointer the caller passed to foreach().
 *
 * Return 0 to continue iterating, any non‑zero value aborts the walk.
 * -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
typedef int (*bsci_block_cb)(const bsci_block_t *block, void *user_data);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
 * Creation / destruction
 *
 *   datadir   – path that contains the BlockSci data files.
 *   error_msg – optional out‑parameter; on failure it points to a static
 *               C string that lives until the next call to any API.
 *
 * Returns a non‑NULL iterator on success; NULL on failure.
 * -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
bsci_iter_t *bsci_iter_open(const char *datadir, const char **error_msg);

/* Release all resources associated with the iterator. */
void bsci_iter_close(bsci_iter_t *it);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
 * One‑shot iteration.
 *
 *   it        – iterator created by bsci_iter_open().
 *   cb        – user supplied callback that will be invoked for each block.
 *   user_data – opaque pointer that is passed unchanged to every cb call.
 *
 * Returns 0 on normal completion.  If the callback returns a non‑zero
 * value, that value is propagated back to the caller.  If an internal
 * error occurs, a non‑zero value (currently –1) is returned.
 * -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
int bsci_iter_foreach(bsci_iter_t *it,
                      bsci_block_cb cb,
                      void *user_data);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
 * Block field accessors – all are cheap, pure‑C calls that just read
 * data from the underlying C++ object.  No allocation is performed.
 * -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
uint32_t bsci_block_height(const bsci_block_t *blk);
uint64_t bsci_block_timestamp(const bsci_block_t *blk);
size_t   bsci_block_tx_count(const bsci_block_t *blk);

/* Returns a pointer to the 32‑byte block hash; *out_len is set to 32.
 * The returned pointer points into BlockSci’s internal memory and must
 * not be freed or modified. */
const uint8_t *bsci_block_hash(const bsci_block_t *blk, size_t *out_len);

#ifdef __cplusplus
}
#endif

#endif /* BLOCKSCI_C_H */
```

